# Brute force
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The brute force recursive solution is `pow(n) = n * pow(n - 1)`.
For both iterative and recursive solution *time complexity:* $$O(n)$$
This will get **Time Limit Exceeded** error, so we need to write a better solution than this.

# Optimized solution
We know $$ x^2 = x * x = (x * x)^1 $$
To calculate $$x^2$$ recursively we will need to make 3 function calls,
`` f(x, 2) --> f(x, 1) --> f(x, 0) ``.
But, to calculate $$ (x * x)^1 $$ we need 2 function calls, `` f(x * x, 1) --> f(x * x, 0)``.

This may seem like a minor change but this reduces the time complexity from linear to logarithmic. And is a significant improvement for larger power.

For even power ``f(x, n) = f(x * x, n / 2)``  
For odd power ``f(x, n) = x * f(x, n - 1)`` 

**Negative power**
$$ x^{-n} = 1 / x^n$$

*NOTE:* Dry run this algorithm for n = 5 and n = 8 (i.e., an even and odd power) for better understanding.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$ O(log_2n) $$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$ O(log_2n) $$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code

```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    double myPow(double x, int n) {

        if (n == 0) return 1.0;
        // even power
        if (n % 2 == 0) return myPow(x * x, n / 2);
        // odd power
        if (n % 2 == 1) return x * myPow(x, n - 1);
        // negative power
        return 1/myPow(x, -n);
    }
};
```
