solutions.content:
# Approach
The main idea behind this approach is to use the binary representation of `n` to efficiently calculate `pow(x, n)`

This approach uses the fact that any number `x` raised to an even power can be obtained by squaring `x` multiple times. This property allows us to reduce the number of multiplications required and hence reduces the time complexity.

1. Initialize a variable `pow` to 1.0, which will store the result of `x` raised to the power of `n`

2. Start with the binary representation of `n` and iterate from its least significant bit to the most significant bit

3. If a bit is 1, it means that the corresponding power of `x` contributes to the final result. So, we multiply `pow` with `x` to include this power in the result

4. After considering the current power of `x`, square `x`. This prepares `x` for the next iteration, where it will be raised to the power of 2

5. Now, we divide `n` with 2

6. Repeat steps 3-5 until all the bits of `n` becomes `0`

The key insight here is that by decomposing `n` into its binary representation, we can identify which powers of `x` are needed to compute the final result. Instead of simply multiplying `x` by itself `n` times, we only multiply when the corresponding bit in `n` is set to 1. This reduces the number of multiplications required

### Example:
`pow(3, 5)` : `3^5`. 5 can be written as `0101` => $2^2+2^0$ => $3^5$ = $3^{2^2}*3^{2^0}$

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(logn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    double myPow(double x, int n)
    {
        if(x == 1 || x == 0)
            return x;

        double pow = 1.0;

        while(n)
        {
            if(n%2 == 1 && n>0)
                pow *= x;
            else if(n%2 == -1 && n<0)
                pow /= x;

            x *= x;
            n /= 2;
        }  

        return pow;
    }
};
```

