# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem is to calculate the value of x raised to the power n. Since n can be a large negative number, positive number, or zero, we need to handle these cases efficiently. Additionally, we can use the divide-and-conquer technique to optimize the power calculation process.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. We'll handle the base cases first: if n is zero, the result is 1, and if n is negative, we'll convert it to a positive number by taking the reciprocal of x and making n positive.
1. We'll then implement a recursive function CalculatePow that will efficiently calculate the power using the divide-and-conquer technique. It recursively calculates the result of x raised to n/2 and then squares it to handle even powers. For odd powers, we multiply the result by x once more.
1. The MyPow function first handles the base cases and then calls CalculatePow to compute the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the solution is O(log n) because the divide-and-conquer approach reduces the number of recursive calls by half in each step.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(log n) as well, as we have log n recursive calls in the call stack due to the divide-and-conquer approach.

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public double MyPow(double x, int n) {
        long N = n;
        if (N == 0) return 1;
        if (N < 0) {
            x = 1 / x;
            N = -N;
        }
        return CalculatePow(x, N);
    }
    private double CalculatePow(double x, long n) {
        if (n == 1) return x;
        double halfPow = CalculatePow(x, n / 2);
        return n % 2 == 0 ? halfPow * halfPow : halfPow * halfPow * x;
    }
}
```

