solutions.content:
**Binary Exponentiation :**

**Like the robots of Asimov, all recursive algorithms must obey three important laws:**
1.  A recursive algorithm must call itself, **recursively.**
2.  A recursive algorithm must have a **base case.**
	`if (n == 0) {
					return 1;
				}`		 
3. A recursive algorithm must change its state and move  **toward the base case.**

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/abe68c78-acda-4118-82cd-557ad7b70592_1642084413.5401745.png)



To handle the case where N=INTEGER_MIN we can use "abs" or long (64-bit) variable
```
class Solution {
public:
    double myPow(double x, int n) {
            //base condition
        if(n == 0) {
            return 1;
        }

        if (n < 0) { 
            n = abs(n);
            x = 1/x;
        }

        return (n % 2 == 0) ? myPow(x*x, n / 2) : x * myPow(x*x, n / 2);
    }
};
```

