For the people experiencing stackOverFlow exception when n = Integer.MAX_VALUE, what I found out was that apparently, stackOverFlow exception occurs even when your number of recursive calls are finite, but of a large number, and there are chances that you are using a call like  `return x*myPow(x,n-1)`. Such type of code makes O(N) recursive calls, which is the cause of the exception when n is very high.
To avoid this, we can use O(n/2) calls and multiply the answer twice in our final answer.
the code is as follows:

       if(n == 0) return 1;

        if(n == 1)return x;

        if(n == -1) return 1/x;

        double half = myPow(x, n/2);

        double rest = myPow(x, n%2);

        return half*half*rest;

such type of a code reduces the number of recursive calls to n/2 instead of n, and we are multiplying the returned value (here, `half`), twice to make up for making half of the required number of calls.

class Solution {
    public double myPow(double x, int n) {

        if(n < 0){
            n = -n;
            x = 1 / x;
        }

        double pow = 1;

        while(n != 0){
            if((n & 1) != 0){
                pow *= x;
            } 

            x *= x;
            n >>>= 1;

        }

        return pow;
    }
}

