# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
while we are iterating over the tokens we have to do operation, so when a operator comes we can do a operation.
to do a operation we need 2 operands so we need previous elements and we will add the result operand after the operation , so we can simply use a list but as we need only 2 recent operands we can use a stack which gives recent elements.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- iterate and when operator comes perform the operation overr last two operands in the stack.
- push the result operand into the stack.
- if operand comes then simply push into the stack.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int evalRPN(String[] tokens) {
        Stack<Integer> st= new Stack<>();
        for(String s : tokens){
            switch(s){
                case "+":
                st.push(st.pop()+st.pop());
                break;
                case "-":
                st.push(-st.pop()+st.pop());
                break;
                case "*":
                st.push(st.pop()*st.pop());
                break;
                case "/":
                int val2 = st.pop();
                st.push(st.pop()/val2);
                break;
                default :
                st.push(Integer.parseInt(s));
            }
        }
        return st.pop();
    }
}
```

