# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The code implements a solution for evaluating a reverse Polish notation (RPN) expression. It uses a stack data structure to keep track of the operands and perform the required calculations based on the operators encountered.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The code iterates through the input tokens array and processes each token based on its type. If the token is an operand, it is pushed onto the stack. If the token is an operator, the code pops the top two operands from the stack, performs the required operation, and pushes the result back onto the stack.

The switch statement is used to handle each operator separately, and the default case is used for operands. The final result is the value left on the stack after all the tokens have been processed.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int evalRPN(String[] tokens) {
        Stack < Integer > stack = new Stack < > ();
        int a, b;
        for (String str: tokens) {
            switch (str) {
                case "+":
                    a = stack.pop();
                    b = stack.pop();
                    stack.push(b + a);
                    break;
                case "-":
                    a = stack.pop();
                    b = stack.pop();
                    stack.push(b - a);
                    break;
                case "*":
                    a = stack.pop();
                    b = stack.pop();
                    stack.push(b * a);
                    break;
                case "/":
                    a = stack.pop();
                    b = stack.pop();
                    stack.push(b / a);
                    break;
                default:
                    stack.push(Integer.parseInt(str));
            }
        }
        System.out.print(stack);
        return stack.pop();
    }
}
```

