# Intuition
Within the tokens vector, we can clearly see that if an operator appears, we must perform that operation on the last two indexes and place the result in place of those two indexes.

# Approach
As can be seen, a stack can be utilised. If we don't find an operator, we will push that token to the top of the stack.
- If we find an operator, we will invoke a helper function (named eval) that will accept 'a stack' and a 'operator string' as input.
- And in that function, I extracted both the no. at the last two indexes, performed the operation on those indexes, and pushed the result back into the stack.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: All the process is done in only one iteration, so it will use O(n) time.


- Space complexity: We are storing an stack of strings, so will use a O(n) space.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    void eval(stack<string> &st, string op){
        long long int b = stoll(st.top());
        st.pop();
        long long int a = stoll(st.top());
        st.pop();
        string res;
        if(op == "+"){
            res = to_string(a+b);
        }
        else if(op == "-") {
            res = to_string(a-b);
        }
        else if(op == "*"){
            res = to_string(a*b);
        }else if(op == "/"){
            res = to_string(a/b);
        }
        st.push(res);

    }
public:
    int evalRPN(vector<string>& tokens) {
        int n = tokens.size();
        stack<string> st;
        for(int i =0;i<n;i++){
            if(tokens[i]=="+" || tokens[i] == "-" || tokens[i] == "/" || tokens[i] == "*"){
                eval(st,tokens[i]);
            }
            else{
                st.push(tokens[i]);
            }
        }
        long long int res = stoll(st.top());
        return res;
    }
};
```

