solutions.content:
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
* First of all I have written down the problem description on a white paper in a clear way. 
* After that I started analyzing the existing test cases, by visualizing how to sort the given digits with the given operations. 
* Also the order of the operands, and which should be the first operand and which should be the second, specially in the division and subtraction operations. 
* After that I have realized that always, it takes the first element to be inserted as the second operand **(operand on the right of the operation)**. 
* so if we have list like this: 
    * [ 3, 2, /] it means => 3 / 2 = 1 (integer divison).
    * [ 5, 2, -, 2, /] it means => 5 - 2 = 3 => 3 / 2 = 1 (integer division). 
* So I have realized that it is a stack problem. 
* And we keep inserting the elements in the stack until we meet one of the operations. 
* Then we have to apply the operation on the top 2 elements where, the element on the top of the stack( the last to be inserted ) should be our second operand, while the element below it should be our first one. 
* then after we calculate the result, we have to insert it again on the top of our stack. 
* and keep repeating the same operation until we finish all the given tokens. 
* After that our result will be the last remaining integer which should be on the top of the stack. 
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
> O(N) where N is the number of the given tokens, as we just iterate over the size of this list once. 
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
> O(N) where N is number of the given tokens. actually the stack will never be the same size as the given tokens, because in the stack I just keep the numbers only, and since the token list contains also some operations, so they will never be in the same size, but this is a higher bound estimation.
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int evalRPN(vector<string>& tokens) {
         stack<int> numbers;
    for (string tok : tokens)
    {
        if (isdigit(tok[0]) || (tok.size() > 1 && isdigit(tok[1])))
            numbers.push(stoi(tok));
        else
        {
            // this is an operation
            int second_operand = numbers.top();
            numbers.pop();
            int first_operand = numbers.top();
            numbers.pop();
            if (tok == "+")
                numbers.push(first_operand + second_operand);
            else if (tok == "-")
                numbers.push(first_operand - second_operand);
            else if (tok == "/")
                numbers.push(first_operand / second_operand);
            else if (tok == "*")
                numbers.push(first_operand * second_operand);
        }
    }
    return numbers.top();
    }
};
```

