# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
First, we need to understand what is **intersection**? In this problem, it simply means **common elements** between the given two arrays.
The problem can be solved in many ways but we have to find the **efficient** solution.
We can use a Hash-Map and an Arraylist to optimize code. Let's look at some examples.

    Example1: nums1 = {1,2,3} and nums2 = {4,5,6}
    Since, there are no common elements,
    We have to return en empty array in this case, {}.

    Example2: nums1 = {1,1,2,3} and nums2 = {1,1,3,4}
    Since, 1 appear two times and 3 appear 1 time.
    So, we will return {1,1,3}.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

We can follow the steps below to better understand the solution:

    1. Create a Hash-Map to store the elements of nums1.
    2. Create an Array-List to store the common elements.
    3. Traverse nums1 to add elements in HashMap.
    4. Traverse nums2 to check for common elements and add in ArrayList.
Traverse the ArrayList, to store the elements into an array. (Since, we have to return an array in this function).

Follow the code below to understand the solution.

            **If this solution helped you, give it an up-vote to help others** 


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] intersect(int[] nums1, int[] nums2) {

    HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>(); // It will store elements of nums1.
    ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(); // It will store common elements of nums1 and nums2.

        //declare i so that it can be used further. (saves space)
        int i; 

        //traverse the array nums1, store element in Key and store its frequency in Value.        
        for(i = 0; i < nums1.length; i++)
        {
            // If map doesn't contain nums1[i] initially, the default value 0+1.
            // If map contain nums1[i] then increase its freq by 1.
            map.put(nums1[i], map.getOrDefault(nums1[i], 0)+1);
        }

        //traverse the array nums2 and check for common elements.
        for(i = 0; i < nums2.length; i++)
        {
            // We need to check two conditions:
            // 1. map should contain nums2[i] element.
            // 2. freq of nums2[i] element must be greater than 1.
            if(map.containsKey(nums2[i]) && map.get(nums2[i]) > 0)
            {                
                list.add(nums2[i]);                         // add it to arraylist.
                map.put(nums2[i], map.get(nums2[i])-1);     // decrease its freq in map.
            }
        }
        // create a new array of list size.
        int [] arr = new int[list.size()];


        // traverse the list and add elements in the array.
        for(i = 0; i < list.size(); i++)
        {
            arr[i] = list.get(i);
        }

        // finally, return the resultant array.
        return arr;
    }
}
```

