# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. First we have to find the array whose size is smaller.
2. By using the unordered_map we calculate the frequency/ count for every element of an array.(i.e smaller in size)
3. Then we find the element of second array(i.e greater in size) in unordered_map:
- If it is found in  unordered_map we push that element of an array in vector(ans) and decrement the frequency/count of that element in unordered_map. 
- We also check freq > 0 then push the element into vector(ans) and decrement the frequency by 1.

***NOTE***: If above both condition are true then only we push the element in the vector. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(m + n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(m + n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> intersect(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {

        vector<int>ans; // answer vector 

        if(nums1.size() > nums2.size()) return intersect(nums2, nums1);
        unordered_map<int, int>mp;

        for(int i = 0; i < nums1.size(); i++)
        {
            mp[nums1[i]]++; // here we count the frequency for every element 
        }

        for(int j = 0; j < nums2.size(); j++)
        {//if the element is found in the unordered_map we decrement the count by 1 and push that element in output vector along with checking the condition that count > 0;
            if(mp.find(nums2[j]) != mp.end() && mp[nums2[j]] > 0)
            {
                ans.push_back(nums2[j]);
                mp[nums2[j]]--;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

