Approach 1: Brute Force (Using two For Loops) || Time = O(n^2), Space = O(n)
**In an interview, always start with brute force/ naive approach, even if you know the optimal solution for a better impression on the interviewer (if you have sufficient time!)
```
vector<int> intersect(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        vector<int>answer;
        int n1 = nums1.size();
        int n2 = nums2.size();
        for(int i = 0; i < n1; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j < n2; j++) {
                if(nums1[i] == nums2[j]){
                    answer.push_back(nums1[i]);  //If there's a common element, we'll add in an aditional vector.
                    nums2.erase(nums2.begin() + j); // we'll remove the common element from the vector so that we don't count it twice
                    n2 -= 1; //as we removed the element, size of that vector will also be reduced
                    break; // this is done because one element of one vector can only match with one element of another vector
                }
            }
        }
        return answer; 
    }

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Approach 2: (Using Hashtable) || Time = O(n), Space = O(n)
Here, we're gonna iterate through any one of two vectors & store all the values in hashmap.
Now, we're gonna check which element from the second vector is actually present inside the hashmap which means a match(intersection) and we'll store that particular element in the additional vector and then remove that element from hashmap.

vector<int> intersect(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        unordered_map<int, int>map; 
        vector<int>answer; //additional vector to store and finally return the output
        for(int i = 0; i < nums1.size(); i++) {
            map[nums1[i]]++; //
        }
        for(int i = 0; i < nums2.size(); i++) {
            if(map[nums2[i]]) {
                answer.push_back(nums2[i]);
                map[nums2[i]]--;
            }
        }
        return answer;
    }

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Approach 3:(Two pointer method, Condition: Vectors/Arrays must be sorted)
Time = O(n) since its given the follow up of the same question, Space  = O(n) or O(1) if we don't return the array.

Whenever input arrays are sorted, always try to use 2 pointer method, cause it'll definitely decrease the time complexity.
Take 2 pointers pointing to starting values of each vector and just compare the values.
IF one value is smaller/greater than the other, increment the pointer accordingly, and 
IF the two values are equal, then store that value in the additional array and increment both pointers since we don't want any duplicates.

vector<int> intersect(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        sort(nums1.begin(), nums1.end());
        sort(nums2.begin(), nums2.end());   
        vector<int>answer;
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while(i < nums1.size() && j < nums2.size()) {
            if(nums1[i] < nums2[j]){
                i++;
            }
            else if(nums1[i] > nums2[j]) {
                j++;
            }
            else {
                answer.push_back(nums1[i]);
                i++;
                j++;
            }
        }
        return answer;
    }

---------------------------------------------------
