# Proof beats
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8cdd1bac-ffb3-4962-b60d-6679a5d8e81d_1673516299.3264258.png)

# Approach 1
- **For each element of the first array**, we **count how many times it occurs**, and enter the data into a **hash table**.
- Now we will iterate over the elements of the second array. If **the current element is in the hash table**, then **we put it in the answer**, after which we decrement. If the result of the decrement is 0, then the element can be removed from the hash table.

# Code
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> intersect(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        unordered_map<int, int> m;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums1.size(); i++) {
            m[nums1[i]]++;
        }
        vector<int> result;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums2.size(); i++) {
            if (m.find(nums2[i]) != m.end()) {
                result.push_back(nums2[i]);
                m[nums2[i]]--;
                if (m[nums2[i]] == 0) {
                    m.erase(nums2[i]);
                }
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```

# Approach 2
- Since **the constraint on element values** ```0 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 1000```, then **instead of a hash table**, it is enough to have **an array of size 1001**.

